    pearls: ["The four bioethical principles: AUTONOMY (patient's right to decide), BENEFICENCE (do good), NONMALEFICENCE (do no harm), JUSTICE (fair distribution of resources) -- these guide every ethical decision in nursing practice","Informed consent requires THREE elements: adequate information in understandable language, patient competence to decide, and VOLUNTARY consent without coercion -- a signed form without true understanding is NOT valid consent","The nurse does NOT obtain informed consent -- the PROVIDER explains the procedure, risks, benefits, and alternatives; the nurse WITNESSES the signature and ADVOCATES for the patient by verifying understanding; if the patient does not understand, the nurse must stop and notify the provider","HIPAA permits sharing patient information with the treatment team on a need-to-know basis WITHOUT patient authorization; authorization IS required for sharing with family (unless the patient consents or is incapacitated), employers, insurance companies, and law enforcement (except mandatory reporting)","A competent patient has the RIGHT to refuse any treatment, including life-saving treatment -- the nurse must document the refusal, ensure the patient understands the consequences, and notify the provider; the nurse CANNOT override the patient's decision","Nurses are MANDATORY REPORTERS: failure to report suspected abuse or neglect is both an ethical violation and a legal offense; reporting is required even if the nurse is not certain abuse occurred -- reasonable suspicion is the legal standard"],
