    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Fluids & Electrolytes Foundations", content: "Body fluid homeostasis is maintained through the balance of fluid intake, output, and distribution between intracellular (ICF, 2/3 of total body water) and extracellular (ECF, 1/3) compartments, separated by selectively permeable cell membranes. Osmotic pressure, primarily determined by sodium concentration in the ECF and potassium in the ICF, drives water movement across compartments. Antidiuretic hormone (ADH) from the posterior pituitary promotes water reabsorption in collecting ducts in response to increased serum osmolality, while aldosterone promotes sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the distal tubule. Electrolyte imbalances — particularly of sodium, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and phosphorus — can produce life-threatening cardiac dysrhythmias, neurological dysfunction, and muscular compromise, requiring the nurse to recognize characteristic signs and implement appropriate corrections." },
    riskFactors: ["Extremes of age: infants have higher total body water percentage (75-80%) with greater surface-area-to-volume ratio increasing insensible losses; elderly have lower body water (45-50%) with decreased renal concentrating ability","Chronic kidney disease (impaired electrolyte excretion and fluid regulation)","Heart failure (neurohormonal activation causes sodium and water retention)","Liver cirrhosis (hypoalbuminemia reduces oncotic pressure, causing third-spacing and ascites)","Diuretic therapy (loop diuretics deplete potassium, magnesium, sodium; thiazides deplete potassium and may cause hyponatremia)","Vomiting, diarrhea, nasogastric suctioning, and fistula drainage (direct electrolyte and fluid losses)","Endocrine disorders: diabetes insipidus (excess water loss), SIADH (excess water retention), hyperaldosteronism (potassium wasting)","Burns (massive fluid shifts from intravascular to interstitial space in first 24-48 hours)"],
