    management: ["Fluid volume deficit (dehydration): isotonic IV fluid replacement (0.9% NaCl or lactated Ringer); oral rehydration if tolerated; monitor vital signs, urine output, and daily weights","Fluid volume excess (overload): fluid restriction (typically 1000-1500 mL/day), sodium restriction (<2 g/day), loop diuretics (furosemide), daily weights, strict I&O, elevate HOB","Hyponatremia: determine if hypervolemic (fluid restrict), euvolemic (SIADH -- fluid restrict, consider tolvaptan), or hypovolemic (give NS); correct sodium slowly (max 8-10 mEq/L per 24 hours to avoid osmotic demyelination syndrome)","Hypernatremia: replace free water deficit (D5W or 0.45% NaCl); correct slowly (max 10-12 mEq/L per 24 hours to avoid cerebral edema); address underlying cause","Hypokalemia: oral KCl supplementation (20-40 mEq) or IV KCl (max 10 mEq/hr peripheral, 20 mEq/hr central with cardiac monitoring); ALWAYS check magnesium (hypomagnesemia prevents potassium correction)","Hyperkalemia (>5.5 mEq/L): emergent treatment if ECG changes present: calcium gluconate (cardiac membrane stabilization), insulin + dextrose (shifts K+ intracellularly), sodium bicarbonate, kayexalate (binds K+ in GI tract), dialysis for refractory cases","Hypocalcemia: IV calcium gluconate (preferred peripheral, less irritating) or calcium chloride (more elemental calcium, central line preferred); oral calcium + vitamin D for chronic management"],
