    assessmentFindings: ["Fluid volume deficit (FVD): thirst, dry mucous membranes, decreased skin turgor, concentrated urine, tachycardia, hypotension, orthostatic changes, sunken fontanels in infants","Fluid volume excess (FVE): weight gain, peripheral edema, JVD, crackles, dyspnea, bounding pulse, elevated BP, decreased urine specific gravity","Hyponatremia (<135 mEq/L): headache, confusion, nausea, lethargy progressing to seizures and coma in severe cases (<120 mEq/L); cellular swelling from hypotonic ECF","Hypernatremia (>145 mEq/L): intense thirst, dry mucous membranes, restlessness, confusion, seizures; cellular dehydration from hypertonic ECF","Hypokalemia (<3.5 mEq/L): muscle weakness, leg cramps, decreased bowel sounds (ileus), flattened T waves, U waves on ECG, respiratory muscle weakness in severe cases","Hyperkalemia (>5.0 mEq/L): muscle weakness (different mechanism than hypokalemia), paresthesias, peaked T waves, widened QRS, bradycardia, cardiac arrest","Hypocalcemia (<8.5 mg/dL): Trousseau sign (carpopedal spasm with BP cuff inflation), Chvostek sign (facial twitching with nerve tap), tetany, prolonged QT, seizures"],
