    pearls: ["PRES is called 'posterior' because the parieto-occipital white matter is preferentially affected -- the posterior circulation has LESS sympathetic innervation and therefore LESS autoregulatory capacity than the anterior circulation, making it more vulnerable to hypertensive breakthrough","MRI FLAIR is the diagnostic gold standard for PRES; the KEY MRI finding is vasogenic edema (bright on FLAIR, elevated ADC) -- NOT cytotoxic edema; if DWI shows restricted diffusion (bright on DWI, dark on ADC map), the 'reversible' part of PRES is being lost and infarction is occurring","Despite its name, PRES is NOT always posterior (atypical patterns involve the frontal lobes, brainstem, or cerebellum in 20-30% of cases) and NOT always reversible (5-15% develop permanent injury, especially with delayed treatment or hemorrhagic transformation)","The three most common causes of PRES are: (1) acute severe hypertension, (2) eclampsia, and (3) calcineurin inhibitor toxicity (cyclosporine, tacrolimus) -- in transplant patients, PRES can occur at NORMAL blood pressures due to direct endothelial toxicity","Blood pressure reduction must be GRADUAL: target 25% MAP reduction in the first hour; overly aggressive BP reduction risks watershed ischemia because the autoregulatory curve has shifted rightward in chronic hypertension","PRES in eclampsia: magnesium sulfate is BOTH the seizure prophylaxis AND the treatment; the definitive cure is DELIVERY; PRES can present postpartum (up to 48 hours or more after delivery)"],
